data.content:
Your test works but uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "Expected count: 3, Actual: 2" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(!=null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Fails clearly if 0 or 2+ matches |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no specialized assertion for "all items match a predicate."
